data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which gives a clear test failure message instead of an `InvalidCastException` if the type is wrong:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The generic `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()` (MSTest v2.2.8+) checks the type and fails with a descriptive message like *"Expected type: EmailHandler. Actual type: SmsHandler."* — much more informative than a crash from a bad cast.
